Year = {{2004}},
Volume = {{40}},
Number = {{1}},
Pages = {{47-53}},
Month = {{JAN-MAR}},
Abstract = {{This paper describe changes in Carabid fauna after a wild fire in June
   1996 in a Pinus pinaster forest in Spain, and also, provides information
   about trap selectivity and the influence of a firebreak on carabid
   abundance. Sampling was carried out from April to October 1997 in the
   burnt area and in a nearby unburnt pine forest. Pitfall traps contained
   three different types of attracting bait and were placed in each area at
   different distances from the firebreak. The colonizing species in the
   burnt area are described and compared to those captured in the control
   pine forest. Data on abundance, species richness, equitability,
   diversity and size differences are given. Seasonal changes and the
   composition of the Carabidae community after the fire are also
   discussed. Greater abundance was observed in the burnt pine forest due
   to the arrival of opportunistic species after the wild fire. Species
   adapted to open areas were captured in the burnt pine zone whereas
   species detected in the control forest are characteristically located in
   areas covered by a lot of vegetation or in grasslands, needing more
   humidity and therefore not tolerant to prevailing post-fire drought
   conditions. (C) 2004 Elsevier SAS. All rights reserved.}},
