Number = {{2}},
Pages = {{324-327}},
Month = {{JUN}},
Abstract = {{Pitfall traps were employed to investigate the effects of post-fire
   salvage logging on abundance of pill beetles (Coleoptera: Byrrhidae)
   across an ecotone from unsalvaged habitat into the interior of a
   salvaged stand in the Canadian boreal forest. Byrrhids (mainly Byrrhus
   geminatus LeConte) were dramatically more abundant at the edge of
   salvaged habitat and more common in the salvage habitat relative to the
   unsalvaged stand. This holarctic beetle, herein reported for the first
   time from Alberta, is characteristic of disturbance, and its abundance
   appears to reflect a relative degree of disturbance over natural
   post-fire conditions.}},
