Volume = {{35}},
Number = {{1}},
Pages = {{217-224}},
Month = {{JAN}},
Abstract = {{In this study, a forest fire occurring in an area within the boundary of
   Izmir province has same vegetational and climatic characteristics as of
   the Mediterranean Region was evaluated. Normalized Difference Vegetation
   Index (NDVI) and Normalized Burn Ratio (NBR) index data pertaining to
   pre- and post-fire periods were produced from Landsat 5 TM imagery. In
   addition, the datasets were compared by calculating the two differences
   of NDVI (dNDVI) and NBR (dNBR) values. The dNDVI data was filtered by
   using an adaptive filter. The filtered data was categorized as unburned,
   low, medium and high levels of fire effectiveness. The levels were
   evaluated to determine the size and distribution, corresponding to the
   landcover types, slope, aspect and elevation classes. For examining the
   changes within the burned area, difference and ratio images were used,
   too. For each band, the images were classified as to one standard
   deviation (SD) threshold value. As a result, the 4th and the 7th bands
   were designated the most appropriate ones for mapping of the burned area
   and dNDVI and dNBR data were found usable for determination fire
   effectivity. The adaptive filtering technique applied is advisable to be
   put into practice as it is a fast and simple method of image enhancement
   to get utilizable and necessary data to be used at fire effectiveness
   levels.}},
