   shrubland and whether seedlings and resprouts incurred different amounts
   of N-2-fixation after fire. We set 18 experimental. res in early autumn
   on 6 plots, subsequently labelling 6 subplots (2 x 2 m(2)) in each
   community with (NH4+)-N-15- N ( 99 atom \% excess). For 9 post-fire
   months we measured net N mineralisation in the top 5 cm of soil and we
   calculated the fraction of legume N derived from the atmosphere (\%
   Ndfa) in seedlings and resprouts. We used two independent estimates of
   the amounts of N derived from non-atmospheric sources in potentially
   N-2-fixing plants: mean soil pool abundance and the N-15-enrichment of
   non-legumes. Despite substantial soil net N mineralisation in all burned
   community types ( about 2.6 g Nm(-2) during the first nine months after
   fire), the \% Ndfa of various legume species was 52 - 99\%. Legumes from
   both grasslands showed slightly higher N-2-fixation values than
   shrubland legumes. As grassland legumes grew in more belowground dense
